  <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6 not-prose">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies disc stack centrifuge systems for cutting oil purification — removing metal fines, chips, and tramp oil from straight cutting oils, draw oils, and rolling oils used in metal forming operations. Operating at 7,000+ Gs, these self-cleaning separators continuously process cutting oil without filter media or consumables. Based in Warren, Michigan, Dolphin Centrifuge has over 40 years of experience in metalworking fluid centrifugation.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="what-is-cutting-oil">What is Cutting Oil?</h2>

  <p>Dolphin Centrifuge, based in Warren, Michigan, supplies purpose-built disc stack centrifuge systems for this application at 7000 Gs with separation down to 0.5 microns. Cutting oil is a <strong>machining lubricant</strong> used in metalworking operations such as turning, milling, drilling, and broaching. Its primary functions are to <strong>dissipate heat</strong> generated at the tool-workpiece interface and to <strong>reduce friction</strong> between the cutting tool and the metal being machined. By performing both roles simultaneously, cutting oil extends tool life, improves surface finish, and enables higher machining speeds.
  </p>

  <p>
    Depending on the application, cutting oils range from light-viscosity neat oils for high-speed aluminum machining to heavy-viscosity formulations for copper and brass broaching. Regardless of viscosity, all cutting oils accumulate metal fines, swarf, and tramp contaminants during use that degrade their lubricating performance.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Dolphin Centrifuge supplies turnkey cutting oil purification systems for machining, drawing, and rolling operations &mdash; removing metal particles as fine as 0.5 microns without consumable filter media.
  </blockquote>

  <!-- ── Need to Recycle ── -->
  <h2 id="need-to-recycle">Need to Recycle Cutting Oil</h2>

  <p>
    Cutting oil is <strong>expensive to purchase and expensive to dispose of</strong>. Premium machining oils with advanced additive packages can cost several dollars per gallon, and contaminated cutting oil is classified as industrial waste subject to strict environmental regulations. Disposal costs continue to rise as regulatory requirements tighten.
  </p>

  <p>
    Beyond cost, environmental regulations increasingly restrict the discharge of oily waste and metal-laden fluids. Many municipalities and states require documented waste manifests and licensed haulers for used cutting oil. A centrifuge-based recycling system dramatically reduces waste volume by returning clean oil to service and concentrating contaminants into a small sludge discharge.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Oil Purchase Savings:</strong> Continuous purification extends cutting oil life by 5&ndash;10x, reducing new oil purchases</li>
    <li><strong>Disposal Cost Reduction:</strong> Only concentrated sludge requires disposal, not the entire oil volume</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Proper oil management helps meet EPA and state environmental requirements</li>
    <li><strong>Smaller Environmental Footprint:</strong> Less waste oil generated per unit of production</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Operation ── -->
  <h2 id="operation">Centrifuge Operation on Cutting Oil</h2>

  <p>
    A disc stack centrifuge processes cutting oil by generating centrifugal forces up to <strong>7,000 Gs</strong> &mdash; thousands of times the force of gravity. At this force level, metal particles as small as <strong>0.5 microns</strong> are driven outward to the bowl wall and captured, while clean oil flows inward through the disc stack and exits the centrifuge.
  </p>

  <p>
    The centrifuge bowl contains a stack of closely spaced conical discs that divide the oil flow into thin layers. This reduces the distance a contaminant particle must travel to reach a collection surface, enabling the capture of extremely fine metal fines that would pass through conventional filters.
  </p>

  <p>
    In <strong>self-ejecting</strong> (self-cleaning) models, accumulated sludge is automatically discharged from the bowl at timed intervals through peripheral ports. The bowl opens momentarily, ejects the collected metal fines and contaminants, then closes and resumes separation &mdash; all without stopping the centrifuge or interrupting the process.
  </p>

  <p>
    The centrifuge typically operates in a <strong>kidney loop</strong> arrangement, continuously drawing contaminated oil from the machine sump or central reservoir, cleaning it, and returning purified oil. This maintains consistent oil quality around the clock without operator intervention.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Benefits ── -->
  <h2 id="benefits">Benefits of Centrifuge Cutting Oil Purification</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Reduced Oil Purchase Costs:</strong> Continuous purification extends cutting oil life dramatically, reducing the frequency and volume of new oil purchases</li>
    <li><strong>Lower Disposal Costs:</strong> Only concentrated metal sludge requires disposal rather than large volumes of spent cutting oil</li>
    <li><strong>Extended Tool Life:</strong> Clean cutting oil free of abrasive metal fines reduces tool wear and extends insert and cutter life</li>
    <li><strong>Improved Part Quality:</strong> Purified cutting oil produces better surface finishes and tighter dimensional tolerances</li>
    <li><strong>Less Machine Downtime:</strong> Continuous centrifuge operation eliminates downtime for oil changes and filter replacements</li>
    <li><strong>No Filter Media Required:</strong> The centrifuge is a purely mechanical separator &mdash; no consumable filter cartridges, bags, or paper to purchase and dispose of</li>
    <li><strong>Consistent Performance:</strong> Unlike filters that lose efficiency as they load, centrifuge separation remains constant regardless of sludge accumulation</li>
    <li><strong>Automatic Operation:</strong> <a href="/industrial-centrifuge-controls/">PLC-controlled systems</a> run unattended with automatic sludge ejection</li>
  </ul>

